```python
def calculate_slippage( pool_tao, pool_price, amount_bought_in_tao ) -> float:
    
    # Compute the amount of alpha in the pool.
    pool_alpha = pool_tao * pool_price
    print ('pool_alpha', pool_alpha)
    
    # Compute the pool constant product.
    pool_constant = pool_tao * pool_alpha
    print ('pool_constant', pool_constant)
    
    # Compute the new amount of pool tao after the buy.
    new_pool_tao = pool_tao + amount_bought_in_tao
    print ('new_pool_tao', new_pool_tao)
    
    # Compute the new amount of pool alpha after the buy (using the constant product).
    new_pool_alpha = pool_constant / new_pool_tao
    print ('new_pool_alpha', new_pool_alpha)
    
    # Compute the amount of alpha actually bought by this operation.
    alpha_bought = pool_alpha - new_pool_alpha
    print ('alpha_bought', alpha_bought)
    
    # Compute the ideal amount of alpha bought using the original price.
    alpha_bought_ideal = amount_bought_in_tao * pool_price
    print ('alpha_bought_ideal', alpha_bought_ideal)
    
    # Compute the absolute slippage in terms of alpha.
    absolute_slippage = (alpha_bought_ideal - alpha_bought)
    print ('absolute_slippage', absolute_slippage)
    
    # Compute the slippage as a percentage based on the ideal amount of alpha bought.
    slippage_percent = 100 * (absolute_slippage / alpha_bought_ideal)
    print ('slippage_percent', slippage_percent)
    
    return slippage_percent

calculate_slippage( pool_tao = 1000, pool_price = 1, amount_bought_in_tao = 100 )
```

The rate of inflation at the beginning of the network is so large that there is *no subnet where inflation does not out pace expected emission drop*. This means there is no reason to sell any of your tokens (they make more money through inflation than they do on your balance) 

However, ***some subnets will have a better return based on the difference between price drop and the inflation ***so it makes sense to swap your tokens out of the subnets with a bad return and instead swap into the subnets with a relatively larger return. 

The graph above shows this relative ratio.

```python
import bittensor as bt
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

number_of_subnets = 25
number_of_blocks = 10000
subnets = bt.subtensor().get_all_subnet_dynamic_info()
num_subnets = len(subnets[1:number_of_subnets])  # Excluding the first subnet

# Initialize the heatmap data
heatmap_data = np.zeros((num_subnets, num_subnets))

for i, subnet_a in enumerate(subnets[1:number_of_subnets]):
    for j, subnet_b in enumerate(subnets[1:number_of_subnets]):
        # Compute return subnet a 
        next_price_a = (subnet_a.tao_in.tao + subnet_a.emission.tao * number_of_blocks) / (subnet_a.alpha_in.tao + 1 * number_of_blocks)
        price_drop_a =  -1 * (next_price_a - subnet_a.price.tao) / subnet_a.price.tao
        inflation_a = ((subnet_a.alpha_out.tao + number_of_blocks) / (subnet_a.alpha_out.tao)) - 1.0
        return_a = inflation_a - price_drop_a
        
        # Compute return subnet b
        next_price_b = (subnet_b.tao_in.tao + subnet_b.emission.tao * number_of_blocks) / (subnet_b.alpha_in.tao + 1 * number_of_blocks)
        price_drop_b =  -1 * (next_price_b - subnet_b.price.tao) / subnet_b.price.tao
        inflation_b = ((subnet_b.alpha_out.tao + number_of_blocks) / (subnet_b.alpha_out.tao)) - 1.0
        return_b = inflation_b - price_drop_b
        
        swap_return_a_to_b = return_b - return_a
        heatmap_data[i, j] = swap_return_a_to_b

# Create the heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
sns.heatmap(heatmap_data, cmap='coolwarm', center=0)
plt.title('Increase in return by swapping from subnet A to subnet B')
plt.xlabel('Subnet B')
plt.ylabel('Subnet A')
plt.show()
```

**Staking on root, my personal understanding** (see how hesitant I am to say emphatically, one more reason why we are deliberately approaching the docs--stuff needs to settled down a bit more).
- If you don't want to be bothered by any dTAO tokens or want to understand them well before diving into them, you can stake to root. Staking to root is in a lot of ways similar to staking now: you stake TAO and unstake TAO. For the stake in root, no TAO <-> dTAO conversions are involved.  
- Equally important is this: your stake in root is like "global stake", i.e., this root stake appears in all the subnets. A simple way to understand this notion is this: This is just like stake TAO today. All staked TAO today appears in all the subnets, i.e., a delegate hotkey's staked TAO appears in all the subnets, right? In the limiting case (i.e., in the "long run") an all-TAO stake almost always imprints more stake weight compared to all-dTAO stake, simply because, in the limiting case a dTAO only approaches to a TAO, but not yet becomes really equal to a TAO. Hence, the moment a delegate hotkey begins holding root stake TAO, this root stake TAO appears as an additional summing component in all the subnets this delegate hotkey is validating, and it has the effect of raising the 51% threshold needed for a rogue attacker in those subnets. 
- Having said that, a delegate may choose not to stake into root because the return on stake can be lesser in root, purely because root doesn't produce any digital commodity and hence does not benefit from TAO<->dTAO exchange value increase that a dTAO-tokenized subnet would accrue.
